F-S-x, Storage Gateway, and the storage decision.

F-S-x is a family of managed third-party filesystems, each purpose-built for a workload E-F-S doesn't fit. F-S-x for Windows File Server speaks S-M-B, stores files in N-T-F-S, and integrates with Active Directory; it's the answer whenever Windows, S-M-B, or Active Directory enters the question. Multi-A-Z runs an active filesystem plus an automatically-promoted standby, with daily backups to S3. F-S-x for Lustre delivers hundreds of gigabytes per second and sub-millisecond latency for H-P-C and M-L, and it links to an S3 bucket, so files appear in the filesystem on first access and processed results export back. F-S-x for NetApp ONTAP, which is multi-protocol N-F-S, S-M-B, and i-S-C-S-I, and F-S-x for OpenZFS are lift-and-shift answers for when you already run NetApp or ZFS.

Storage Gateway bridges on-premises to AWS, presenting cloud storage as local storage. S3 File Gateway, over N-F-S or S-M-B, lands on-prem files directly in S3. F-S-x File Gateway caches a central F-S-x for Windows at a branch office. Volume Gateway, over i-S-C-S-I, in Cached or Stored mode, gives block storage backed by S3 or E-B-S snapshots. And Tape Gateway, a virtual tape library over i-S-C-S-I, replaces physical tape libraries with your backup software unchanged.

Here's the file-storage decision, since the names don't reveal the fit. Linux N-F-S shared across instances is E-F-S. Windows S-M-B with Active Directory is F-S-x for Windows. Maximum throughput for H-P-C or M-L is F-S-x for Lustre. Multi-protocol lift-and-shift from NetApp is ONTAP, and ZFS features are OpenZFS. On-prem clients landing files in S3 is S3 File Gateway. The default answer to most generic shared-file-storage questions is E-F-S for Linux and F-S-x for Windows.
